You have to create fields named the same way you specified in the .fxml file (with `fx:id=&quot;...&quot;`), for each component and use the `@FXML` annotation.

For example you have to add `@FXML private BorderPane borderPane2;` to access the border pane object.

The best way to implement that is using the **MVC design pattern**.
References:
- [Wikipedia MVC](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Model%E2%80%93view%E2%80%93controller)
- [Useful article](https://edencoding.com/mvc-in-javafx/)
- [MVC observations](https://stackoverflow.com/a/23188708/19544859) (StackOverflow answer by [jewelsea](https://stackoverflow.com/users/1155209/jewelsea))
- [MVC really good example](https://stackoverflow.com/a/32343342/19544859) (StackOverflow answer by [James_D](https://stackoverflow.com/users/2189127/james-d))

Basically the **View** is the GUI (your .fxml files), the **Model** is the classes you use (for example you could have a Student, a Professor, and some other classes you need to implement a school score system), and the **Controller** is where you make changes to the model data and update the View consequently.

I&#39;ll leave here a *very simple example* which implements the MVC pattern:

**Result**:

[![enter image description here][1]][1]

**Project structure**:

    src
     |
     +- application (package)
          |
          +-- Controller.java
          |
          +-- Main.java
          |
          +-- Test.fxml
          |
          +-- application.css

**Main.java** class:

