There is no such dictionary, but you can override the default behavior and customize the type resolver. 

Assuming you have this Graphql schema

    type Product {
        sku: ID!
    }
    
    type Address {
        streetName: String
    }
    
    type Query {
        product(sku: ID!): Product
        addresses: [Address]
    }

And you want to use a different class name for Product

    class ThisIsTheProduct {
        private String SKU;
    }

You can implement `RuntimeWiringConfigurer` for register the tpye and the name. 

    @Configuration
    class GraphQlConfig implements RuntimeWiringConfigurer {
    
    
        @Override
        public void configure(RuntimeWiring.Builder builder) {
            ClassNameTypeResolver typeResolver = new ClassNameTypeResolver();
            typeResolver.addMapping(ThisIsTheProduct.class, &quot;Product&quot;);
            builder.type(new TypeRuntimeWiring.Builder().typeName(&quot;Product&quot;).typeResolver(typeResolver).build());
        }
    }

Your query in the controller in this example will be something like this: 

    @Controller
    class ProductQuery {
    
        @QueryMapping
        public ThisIsTheProduct product(@Argument String sku) {
            return new ThisIsTheProduct(sku);
        }
    
        ...
    }


